story: Sal and I have been running for nearly 10 years, it was all her idea! I was never the cross country champ at school in fact I was always last, but running with Sal (not forgetting my fur babies) gives it a whole new enjoyability! We want to keep challenging ourselves and felt that this was a great way to increase the challenge and raise money for a fabulous cause. We have both been affected by Cancer in our families and one of our closest friends lost her husband from this dreadful disease in Jan 2020 so please dig deep and encourage this mammoth task we have undertaken! It begins on the 1st of January and we hope to complete it by the 31st Dec!

story: Thank you to anybody that chooses to read this fully. Me and my son (7)will be doing a 24 hour gaming livestream together. To raise money towards cancer support. We lost a very dear lady to cancer 7 years ago. She was my fiance and she is his mum. She was only 27 years old and was taken from us all way before her time.He never got to know the type of woman she was, he struggles every single day with the loss of his mum. It is my goal to raise awareness for other familys going through these same struggles, to help other young children in his situation to get the help they need at the right time. Many thanks for listening to a very brief version of our story and we hope to concour this together.

pageSummary: Triathlon challenge for Macmillan Cancer Support
pageSummaryWhat: Triathlon challenge for Macmillan Cancer Support
story:
As most will know, I lost both my parents to Cancer. Also  so many of you would have been effected by this illness at some point in your lives too, either directly or indirectly.  

SO....... I have set myself a challenge to complete my first Triathlon on the 13th June 2021 at Windsor.

 Those that know me, know I love a challenge and I’m determined when I set myself one. I have never owned or even ridden a road bike!! - I must be bonkers!! I’ve just bought myself a bike and I am also a terrible swimmer!! However, with hard work, grit and determination I will get round the course in order to raise money for the wonderful Macmillan nurses . 

Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can. 

Any donation, no matter how big or small would be hugely appreciated and would go some way to helping out Macmillan.

Thank you for reading 🙏

story:
Hello friends, 

This year has not been easy for anyone. After a turbulent year, I’ve decided to do something very out of character- running. Now, as most of you know, I am not a naturally gifted athlete (unfortunately), but in aid of a good cause I’m setting out to run 100km in 30 days. 

This great cause is Macmillan Cancer Support, a charity very close to my families heart, providing support for those suffering from cancer. I will be documenting my (probably quite painful) athleticism and any donation to this brilliant cause would be greatly appreciated. I would really appreciate your support and I hope my struggle at running will at least make one or two of you laugh. 

I will be running 100km in 30 days from the 1st January- 30th January 2021 and trying to raise as much as money as possible to help those most in need of support. Happy new year everyone.

Thanks for supporting my fundraising. Macmillan Cancer Support is here to help everyone with cancer live life as fully as they can, providing physical, financial and emotional support. charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
eventName: Catherine’s 100km Challenge for British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support.

This January I will be running 100km in memory of my Grandad who sadly passed away last year on the 29th December. As this charity means a lot to our family, I will also have their support as they look to add to the 100km by completing their own running or walking challenges. 

 The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

pageSummary: I am cutting off approx 15" of my hair because I want to raise money and donate the hair for wigs
pageSummaryWhat: I am cutting off approx 15" of my hair
story:
Thank you for visiting my page! I am raising money for Lymphoma Action and British Heart Foundation by cutting off around 15" of my hair. I plan to donate the hair that is cut off to The Little Princess Trust who make wigs for young people who have lost their hair due to cancer treatment or other conditions. I previously cut off my hair 6 years ago for LPT and raised money from this to donate to two charities. This time I have chosen different charities to donate the money to.

I have chosen BHF for my Grandma who died when I was 2 and a half after suffering several heart attacks.

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures.

story:
As many of you know I lost my brother Gary due to a sudden cardiac event in October, something we still haven’t come to terms with.   What perhaps you don’t know is that Gary and I (and our brother Glen)  lost our Dad aged 54 from a sudden cardiac event and his siblings also had cardiac issues as did our Grandad.  .  Please help  me raise some money for vital research into familial heart disease.  Dry January is my chosen challenge to do this. Wish me luck!!

story:
Many of you will already know that my dad survived a sudden cardiac arrest in December 2019. He was extremely lucky as there happened to be a defibrillator at the sports centre and CPR was started almost immediately. We are hoping to give something back by helping to raise money for the British Heart Foundation. Our aim is to walk 100km from now until the end of January! Any donation is very much appreciated! 


Go The Distance .100 Km . For your health ;for the challenge ;for the cause.Becoming a BHF Champion and improving health and well being and welcoming 2021 with new healthy habits .Thank you so much to everyone that has signed up so far its been a fantastic effort .Please do join our strava group also https://www.strava.com/clubs/gothedistance100k .

pageSummary: I'm giving up beer for January because I drink too much beer
pageSummaryWhat: I'm giving up beer for January
story:
I'm making a bit of a life change in January and giving up drinking alcohol for the month.

My Dad passed away in April 2020, partly due to an undiagnosed heart condition, and the British Heart Foundation are struggling to achieve their normal levels of donation during the pandemic, so trying to collect a bit of cash for them on the way can hopefully help to keep me going! 

I've not tried to do anything like this before, and haven't gone probably more than 10 days without drinking since I was 18, so this is long overdue (!) and I'm hoping that doing this challenge can make some positive long-term changes. 

The British Heart Foundation says:

The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

As I'm sure you are aware, sadly my step father Michael (Mike) Gray suddenly passed away due to chronic heart failure on the 23rd December 2020.

As we can only have a small private ceremony due to Covid-19, I'm asking if people would like to donate to the British Heart Foundation in Mike's memory, it doesn't matter how small.

Mike was a wonderful, caring husband/father/step-father/brother and grandfather who is going to be missed dearly by many but he WILL continue to live on in our hearts and our memories.

Thank you.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

eventName: Land's End to zjohn O Groat's
pageSummary: I am walking a virtual 874 miles #LEJOG9 because I want to raise money for BHF's valuable research
pageSummaryWhat: I am walking a virtual 874 miles #LEJOG9
story:
Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures.

In February 2020 I was rushed to hospital with severe chest pain and shortness of breath. After being transferred to Royal Papworth hospital I was fitted with three stents in two of my main coronary arteries that were found to be 94% blocked.  

My recovery hasn't been easy, mainly due to Covid-19 restrictions, but I know the best way to improve my fitness and maintain my health is by walking.  That's why I've decided to sign up for a virtual walk from Land's End to John O Groat's, a total of 874 miles!  Not in one day of course, I have exactly one year to complete the challenge starting on 1st January 2021. 

I know this will help me in my quest for better health, and it seems right to raise money for BHF at the same time.  I've set my target at £874, that's just £1 for every mile I walk.If you can sponsor me even for just one of those miles I'd be really grateful. 

It's an ambitious challenge, but one that I'm determined to succeed at.  I'll be posting regular updates of my progress on this page.  I'll be starting with short distances but will be aiming to increase the distance of each walk over time. Thank you for your support. 

Morag x

story:
"In an instant one is born and in an instant one dies. In an instant one come to this world, and in an instant one disappears. One, who recognizes the Shabad and merges into it, is not afflicted by death."

Thank you for clicking on this link. This page has been set up in loving memory of Sohan Singh Bhoday who sadly passed away on 25th December 2020 from a cardic arrest.

Your donations will go to help the British Heart Foundation whose vision is a world free from the fear of heart and circulatory diseases and raise money to research cures and treatments.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. pageSummary: Self confessed chocoholic giving it up for BHF ❤️ because For Oscar, who had an aortic stent during lockdown
pageSummaryWhat: Self confessed chocoholic giving it up for BHF ❤️
story:
The pandemic is the biggest challenge we've faced in our 60 year history. And it's led to us being forced to make the devastating decision to cut our 2020 research budget in half. So the truth is, we've never needed people like you more. 

Virtual fundraising challenges like Dechox are a way to help us keep up the pace of progress. Your willpower will be funnelled into ground-breaking science and support for the people who need us most.

Because despite everything else happening at the moment, heart and circulatory diseases are still the world's biggest killers. For the sake of our mums and dads, brothers and sisters, grandparents and friends - we can't drop the ball now.

Hi all! Thank you for visiting my page. Anyone who knows me, will know that I am not a runner by any means of the word. However, myself and a good friend have teamed up and have vowed to run 13km in September for BHF. Considering I can not run for more than 5 mins at the moment, this is a big and scary task. However, I am so excited to embark on the journey. Any spare change you may have to help support me in this, would be extremely appreciated. 


LET’S DO THIS!

Name: Emily's Bath Half

charity.description: With your support, we aim to fund over £100 million of research each year into all heart and circulatory diseases and the things that cause them. Heart diseases. Stroke. Vascular dementia. Diabetes. They're all connected, and they're all under our microscope. Together we can beat heartbreak forever.
charity.name: British Heart Foundation
story: Thanks for visiting my page. I'm raising money for the British Heart Foundation and I'd be so grateful for your support. The BHF has helped halve the number of people dying from heart and circulatory disease in the UK but sadly every day hundreds of people lose their lives. It's only thanks to support from people like us that the BHF can create new treatments and discover new cures. £24 could pay for two hours of research by an early career scientist, but every pound helps so please give what you can to help me hit my target. Thanks!

charity.description: We fundraise to enhance Great Ormond Street Hospital’s ability to transform the health and wellbeing of children and young people. Donations help to fund advanced medical equipment, child and family support services, pioneering research and rebuilding and refurbishment.
charity.name: Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity
story:
This January, I'm kickstarting 2021 by taking part in Running off Christmas. I'll be running 31 miles throughout the month to raise money for Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity.

Many of you are aware of Sophies complex brain malformation and if it wasn't for the wonderful doctors and nurses at GOSH, she wouldn't be thriving as well as she is. Every visit and every stay, those at Great Ormond Street Hospital go above and beyond to make sure her time there goes as best as can be; every doctor and nurse speaks to her like she is the most important small person in the world, they make sure she fully understands what is going on, they are open and honest and they really do all they can for every child.

Every penny we raise can make such a difference in ensuring GOSH continue to make life saving discoveries and ensure every child has the best possible chance at fulfilling their potential.

story: Great Ormond Street Hospital supports seriously ill children from all over the UK. Every day 619 children and young people arrive at GOSH to receive care and life saving treatments to ensure they can continue to lead healthy lives. Since 2012, Premier Inn and Restaurants have been proud partners of Great Ormond Street Hospital Charity and we know our passionate teams have taken part in many brilliant fundraising events as well as volunteering at national events around the country and at the hospital. During these uncertain times our teams continue to achieve incredible things, challenging themselves to conquer their Everest and take care of their wellbeing. We are looking to continue the fantastic fundraising achieved through our partnership by supporting our teams in their creative and dedicated ways of personal achievement. We are #innthistogether and together, we can continue our incredible work.

pageSummaryWhat: I would like to raise money
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I have decided to do Dry January, for anyone that knows me well, you will now how much I like a drink or two.  Therefore, this is going to be a very tough challenge for me!

I would like to raise money for Great Ormond Street as I have seen so many sick children being taken care of there and it makes you realise how lucky many of us are to have healthy, happy children.

I would be extremely grateful for any donations you can give, I know it’s a hard time for everyone so please spare whatever you can! No amount is too little!

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I'm running 31 miles in January with my daughter, Hannah aged 8. She has donated toys to children's charities and wanted to get her hair shaved off to raise money.  Anyone who knows Hannah will know that she hates getting hot and sweaty and has stopped some of her after school activities because of this! This will be a mission for her but I'm sure she will manage her 31 miles for such a good charity.

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I wouldn’t usually have chosen to fundraise for the NHS. But, I’m worried now that so much of the foundational resource will ( completely  necessarily) be redirected to addressing the COVID 19 pandemic. I don’t want any child to miss out on life changing treatment at this wonderful hospital. Please help me to keep this provision running. Xx 

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. After all the festivities and with the cold and wet weather January can bring, your donations to support Great Ormond Street Hospital's life saving work will keep me going when I need it most. It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button! GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

Now that you're here, why not donate a little change in aid for charity. I am aiming to reach my target of £3000 which will all be donated to 'Great Ormond Street Hospital Children's Charity' (GOSH).

Around 5 children a day lose their life to a rare disease and GOSH have been working extremley hard to prevent this from happening. 

I know people who have lost their son/daughter due to a rare disease and as a father myself, i can only imagine how tough that would be to accept.

Myself and my friend Andrew will be cycling across London to visit 13 professional football stadiums which will be around 70 miles in total.

Any donation will be helpful and appreciated

story:
As many of you may know, GOSH holds a very close place to my heart. I was born with a hole in my heart and faced a very challenging start to life; where I was extremely unwell and required surgery to patch up my heart. If it wasn't for the amazing life saving operation and then the continuous care, which was carried out by GOSH, then I wouldn't be here. 

Therefore, this January, I am going to try to run 31 miles throughout the month. This may not sound a lot but for someone who has never been any good at running further than 200m (400m at a very very big push) running on average a mile a day should be a decent challenge. 

I would be grateful for any donations through this challenging time in our lives, your donations to support GOSH will go towards providing children with life saving work which I was lucky enough to have received when I was a baby.

It's quick, easy and secure to donate, just press the Give Now button!GOSH's patients, families and staff need your support now more than ever.

story:
Daniel was a beautiful, bright and funny little boy, he loved PJ masks, animals, watching telly and eating chocolate cake. Daniel was first diagnosed with acute myeloid leukaemia when he was 8 months of corrected age, he’d been born prematurely and battled through this, spending 4 months at home before staying in Great Ormond Street children’s hospital for 5 and a half months undergoing 4 round of chemotherapy. In 2017, Daniel relapsed with 2 different types of cancer his original AML and acute lymphoblastic leukaemia, something which GOSH had never seen as a relapse - usually this presents first line and typically very difficult to treat. Daniel endured 7 weeks of painful chemotherapy, and died due to complications of parainfluenza, normally something that is a minor illness in children with a good  immune system. Daniel died 9 days later after spending this time on a ventilator, he was strong and amazing throughout, but unfortunately his body could no longer continue. 

 Despite Daniel’s ill health, his little spirit and joy always shone, he was a joy to be around and he was our sunshine, he made us grow and be happy, 

 Sometimes people ask how do I carry on? Some days, I don’t know, but I know I have to continue to carry on Daniel’s legacy, and by running and raising funds for this amazing charity really does help me to carry on. 

 Daniel’s memorial fund raises money for family accommodation,  which we really benefited from being housed close to Daniel when he was on the paediatric Intensive care unit (PICU), the fund also raises money for the play workers who do such amazing work, we benefited from the help of Jen who Daniel loved, as did we, and also to raise money for hard to treat leukaemia’s that are kinder and tailor made for children. 

 I appreciate that I am always running, never running the best times, but I keep going because of Daniel and I really appreciate all of your support in helping me to honour Daniel’s memory, and to fundraise for an amazing charity.

 Thank you all in advance, I really appreciate it x

story:

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

After months of suffering with many different ailments and being given tablets, blood infusions and hospital procedures, on 1st December, 2020 our strong Mum was told the devastating news that she had lung cancer that had already spread to her liver and lymph nodes. One of her first reactions being “I’m a fighter, I can fight this”.

The lung cancer nurse at North Tees mentioned that she had looked through my mums medical records and she said that all the signs were there. Due to the pandemic, and the fact that people can’t see their doctor face to face, she explained that they are sadly seeing more and more patients coming in who should have really been picked up sooner.

Mum was discharged from hospital ‘medically fit’ to go home on 14th December. By 18th December we had made the heart breaking decision to take her into a home, Ayresome Court care home. There, she was given the most attentive 24/7 care that she needed, and the wonderful staff there ensured that she was comfortable and out of pain. 

On the morning of 22nd December, following covid rules, we each had an hour with mum. And, just as the greatest mum that ever lived should do, she waited until she had seen us all, before she took her last breaths, holding her son Robert’s hand.

Rather than sending flowers, we would love you to donate to  Cancer Research UK, in the name of Myrna, with the hope that money raised will help diagnose people more quickly and support the families.

story:
Walk 2021 in 2021 - Year Charity Fundraiser 

1st July 2021 would have been my sister Jacqui’s 50th Birthday and therefore a significant anniversary in her life.  Jacqui tragically died suddenly in July 1997 from an undiagnosed heart condition and was taken from her family far too young at the age of just 26 years old. I was only 21. 

From the day Jacqui died my parents (Geoff and Jenny), dedicated the rest of their lives to fundraising for charities close to Jacqui’s heart but most for the most part this was supporting ‘The Children’s Trust’ in Tadworth, Surrey which helps children with brain injuries and neuro-disabilities. 

Geoff and Jenny spent many hours and weekends at horse race courses across the UK, where they would set up ‘Mascot Races’, with all manner of furry animals, reptiles and even utilities turning up to entertain the crowds with a one furlong race during the various race meetings. 

Dad was always most excited to discover the most unusual mascot and during many conversations would play ‘Guess the mascot I have now found?’. Between them, Mum and Dad won numerous awards in recognition of their charitable efforts and Dad was even asked to be a torchbearer for the 2012 Paralympics. 

Those of you who knew my parents would know that they both suddenly deteriorated in health during 2018 & 2019 and both died of prostate and pancreatic cancer within a year of each other.

I am exceptionally proud of my sister’s and Mum and Dad’s charitable achievements and have therefore been inspired to complete a fundraising event ‘Walk 2021 in 2021’ in their honour by targeting to walk 2021 kilometres (or 1256 miles) during the year of 2021 and raising funds for both ‘The Children’s Trust’ and ‘Cancer Research’.

If you are able to provide a donation towards my fundraising event, it would be much appreciated whilst remembering three very special people for me. Thank you.

eventName: Cancer Research UK London Winter Run 2021
pageSummary: I am running  the 2021 Winter 10k because The money you donate saves lives
story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my Justgiving page.

As you may already know, I have combined my love of running with fundraising for many years and I have repeatedly asked my friends to open their wallets, which they have, time after time, willingly. I’m doing it again but this year things are a bit different. On the 9th of September 2020  I found out that I had breast cancer. To say that it came as a bit of a shock is a gargantuan understatement. I’m a fit, healthy, non-smoker so was lulled into a false sense of security that I was at minimal risk. However, my diagnosis, which identified the type of cancer and effective treatment pathway, was made possible as a result of years and years of dedicated research. I am very lucky. A series of good clinical decisions (referral, biopsies -all of them) detected my cancer early  and allowed me the option of the least invasive surgery to remove it, before it had spread and eliminating the need for follow up chemotherapy. My treatment is ongoing but I am thrilled to be back running and have set myself the target of the 7th of February to run 10k. 

Cancer Research UK is facing a massive hole in funding this year and, whilst I know that 2020 has been ‘challenging’ (feel free to insert your own adjective here) for everyone, their work has undoubtedly saved my life and will continue to improve outcomes for cancer patients. So if you can spare a few quid, that would be amazing.

story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

I am Katie from Mae Mae Cakes. Recently, my grandfather lost his battle to cancer. Cancer has also sadly affected other members of my family. Around ten years ago my grandmother was diagnosed with cancer. Fortunately due to the research that has been carried out, doctors were able to remove and treat her cancer and she is healthy and well today. However for many cases, like my grandfather, this is not the case.

This is a disease that has taken and is taking too many lives and I have decided that anything that I am able to do to help find a cure I would like to do.

Over on my Instagram page @x.mae.mae.cakes.x I am running a raffle for a batch of any twelve cupcakes of your choice and the rules are as follows:

  • Donate a minimum of £3 to this JustGiving Page.
  • Live in area surrounding Bermondsey so I am able to deliver or you can pick up the prize easily.
  • When making a donation leave your name so that I can enter it into a randomiser to choose a winner.
  • Make sure to leave details so that I can contact you if you win.
The winner will be chosen in 2 weeks time so be quick and most importantly good luck 🤞.

This innovative grant is dedicated to groundbreaking research and saving millions of lives around the world. Zumba® has touched the lives of men and women globally through dance-fitness, music and community and it strives to make moves in the fight against cancer. My aim with your help is to finish 2020 thinking of others and contribute beat cancer dancing together.

story:
Belle has decided she wants to do what I did and cut her hair for charirty. She has been asking to do it for a few months but wanted to make sure she really wanted to have it done before organising anything.

Belle is looking to have her cut to just below he shoulders, hopefully on her birthday, 4th January (but we need to find somewhere with appointments 1st). story:
Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page.

We are Ben Watkins & Chris Lewis. 23 year olds from Tredegar, South Wales + Sudbury, England.

Myself and Ben met at university in first year halls and from here continued to live together.

Having both now graduated from university and in our respective jobs, we regularly keep in contact.

Fitness is a massive part of our lives, of course from a physical standpoint but perhaps more importantly for our own mental health.

We recently spoke about how with gyms constantly reopening and then closing due to the ongoing COVID-19 pandemic we both wanted something to aim for and be accountable towards.

We came to the goal of running 5km everyday for 60 days over the months of January and February. Equating to a total distance of 300km ran each. Thats the same distance as running from Swansea to London, to put it in perspective.

Whilst we are doing this venture, we want to raise some money for 3 charities that are close to our hearts - MIND, Cancer Research and The National Blood Clot Alliance.

Mind is a charity that supports individuals who are experiencing mental health issues. They campaign to improve services, raise awareness and promote understanding. Both of us have suffered from our own mental health problems around depression and anxiety. Given the uncertain times we find ourselves in and mental health being a more prominent issue than ever before, we want to play our part to help this amazing charity.

As for Cancer Research, it speaks for itself really. 1 in every 2 people in the UK will be diagnosed with Cancer at some point in their lifetime. Personally (Chris), I lost a Grandfather at a young age to Lung Cancer. I will never get to have the experiences with my Grandfather that every young man growing up would want. I (Ben) have also lost one of my best mates and had family members be affected by this terrible illness. Cancer Research does amazing work everyday to identify causes and develop strategies for prevention, diagnosis, treatment and ultimately find a cure. Contributing to this charity would mean a lot on a personal level both of us.

The finally charity is The National Blood Clot Alliance (NBCA). The NBCA is a non-profit, voluntary health organization dedicated to advancing the prevention, early diagnosis and successful treatment of life-threatening blood clots. I will be running for this charity due to the impact it has had one of my best mates Sam. Sam is currently studying out in America where he has had to undergo 2 surgeries to remove blood clots. When speaking to Sam he has explain how much this charity has helped him and recommend this charity in order to raising awareness and a donation for them.

At the end of the 60days, your donations will be split evenly in 3 ways with total raised going to each respective charity.

We would both like to thank you for your support and donations in advance, however small or large.

To help get the word out, please feel free to share the link to our page on your socials on Facebook, Instagram, Twitter etc!

Thanks Again!

story:
Due to the ongoing Coronavirus saga it hasn’t been possible to have a real-life partyyyy to celebrate Laura’s 70th Birthday, so we decided to set up a WhatsApp group and rope in 70+ of Laura’s friends into recording a “short” video, about her, a simple message or song.

To get the ball rolling I pledged to cycle 70 miles and donate £70 to charity if we hit the magic number, so here we are!

Any money donated is on top of my £70.

I don’t expect anyone to dig really deep so soon after Christmas but if you can spare any money that would be really appreciated.

I have chosen Cancer Research as the charity as Laura’s family and mine have lost someone dear to the disease and no doubt many of you have also been affected. 

Here’s to a better 2021 and thank you very much for your donations and wonderful videos.. 

Adam

pageSummary: We are running 5k every day of January because In memory of Joanne Harrison and Sam Charles
pageSummaryWhat: We are running 5k every day of January
story:
Well this year has been particularly difficult for all of us in many ways but some have suffered far worse with loss of a family member or a close friend.

We have decided to start the year on a positive foot and run 5K every day of January this will amount to 155K, people who know us will know that both of us being what you could call short with our little legs this is definitely a challenge for us haha. Jokes aside we are going to be doing this in aid of 2 charities,

1) Mind mental health... over recent years We have lost 2 very close friends to mental health Paul Kennedy back in April 2014 and Max Webb in March 2020, This hit us hard and even more so for their families, but I just want to do something positive in their names in hope that anything raised will help others in the future.

2) Marie Curie (Holme Towers).... once again lost 2 beautiful family members to cancer Joanne Harrison and more recently Sam Charles. Holme Towers done such a great job in their care and once again would like to raise money to help them continue with the great care they provide for not just the person that is Battling this awful disease but also the support that they give their loved ones at their bedside.

We totally understand that with the current year we have had money is tight especially just after Christmas but anything you can spare would be greatly appreciated and will go a long way to helping these charities to continue doing what they do best.

As we can’t put 2 charities on one page we have to share them separately so please donate to your preferred choice Thanks!!!!

Thanks to everyone who has taken the time to read this and put in their hard earned money it means a lot.

Thanks Dave and Rach

pageSummary: 10000 because Set your fitness goal (310,000 steps - 10,000 a...
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

charity.description: Marie Curie provides care and support for people living with any terminal illness across the UK. Our nurses work night and day in people’s homes and our hospices offer specialist care. We also support people emotionally, provide practical information, and match them with trained volunteers.
charity.name: Marie Curie
pageSummary: 310000 because Set your fitness goal (310,000 steps - 10,000 a...
story:
Every day of your life matters from the first to the last. We believe that everyone living with a terminal illness should be able to get the most from the time they have left, however hard that may sometimes feel. 
We'll be here for you and your family when you may feel like no-one else is, to help you cope when you don't know how. Marie Curie Nurses care for you in your home, when you need them most, day or night. Our hospices are at the heart of communities around the UK. And our trained volunteers and advisers are here for you with practical information and support when you don't know what to do next or just need to talk. 
We'll be by your side with care and support every step of the way, bringing light in the darkest hours.

pageSummary: Attempting vegan diets for the whole of January because They do amazing work for animals and environment
pageSummaryWhat: Attempting vegan diets for the whole of January
story: We want your help in creating awareness of the environmental issues that are threatening our natural world. We have fallen into many habits ourselves that are to the detriment of such things and one of those is our diet, so we are saying goodbye to steaks, lasagna and fried chicken and saying hello to lentils, chickpeas and tofu for the whole month of January 2021! This is not only to aid in helping us towards a healthier lifestyle, but to help create a better world for future generations and give them the best chance to succeed through a more sustainable livelihood that is better for our planet. WWF is one of the charities that is carrying out meaningful work to preserve our natural world and their resources can help everyone understand how to positively act within their lifestyles to achieve the same goals. We understand it has not been the easiest time for everyone recently, but if it is within your means to donate, it would be greatly received. Thank you, from David and Valentina!

We’re the world’s leading independent conservation organisation. And we’re building a future where people and nature thrive together.

charity.name: WWF-UK
pageSummary: This year we are raising money because we wish to support animal conservation
pageSummaryWhat: This year we are raising money
story:
As a family we are really passionate about animals and finding out all about them and what we can do to protect them and their habits. Our kids are really interested in learning about animals and our son in particular is fascinated by seeing them in their natural environments - something that we hope he will get the chance to do alot of as he grows up. 

We understand that in order for us, our children and generations to come to be able to see the varied range of species the world has to offer, that we all must do our bit to protect them and the world they live in.

This not only gives us the opportunity to raise money to support conservation, research and protection, it also allows us many opportunities to teach our children of the importance of this from visiting places far away to seeing amazing animals in nature, to simply observing the wildlife on a local park walk.

That's why this year we are hoping to support the WWF in many ways throughout 2021 starting with The Big Winter Wander. This is something that's easy to do, a walk we can plan for ourselves and do in our own time, at our own pace having plotted a comfortable and manageable distance. This also makes it super easy for you to get involved too! 


To find out more or to join in the event yourself follow this 

link: https://www.wwf.org.uk/events/winter-wander?pc=AUT005001&gclsrc=aw.ds&&gclid=Cj0KCQiAoab_BRCxARIsANMx4S579jm6BlT1KCSTFkrJ8dhH6pZBkU68zwEy3xVdGeQ-uafGdUin00AaAo9cEALw_wcB


If you are able to leave a small donation on our page to help support we would be very grateful!

Thank you for visiting our page!

The Boyd's 🐾

pageSummary: I want to raise funds to help our wildlife because My Guide are campaigning for Wildlife corridors
pageSummaryWhat: I want to raise funds to help our wildlife
story:
IF YOU GO DOWN TO THE WOODS TODAY... You might notice there's less wildlife than there used to be. That's because half of all UK species are in decline were losing our precious red squirrels, hedgehogs and birds at an alarming rate. By taking part in The Big Winter Wander, you and your friends and family can reconnect with our country's beautiful wildlife and help protect it. The funds you raise will help us campaign to protect wildlife here, and around the world. Nature has been there to offer us comfort during difficult times, and now its our time to give back.

The latest in WWF’s flagship research series, the Living Planet Report, shows that our planet’s wildlife populations have now plummeted by 68% since 1970 – and there are no signs that this downward trend is slowing.

My Guides, 1st Myland Guides are campaigning for developers to include Wildlife corridors in all developments in the future. Check out 'Let Wildlife Walk'!!

pageSummary: We are going to Brandon Marsh to explore & learn because It is a cause we believe is so important!
pageSummaryWhat: We are going to Brandon Marsh to explore & learn
story: We are setting off on a Big Winter Wander because for us as a family this is so important to us. Getting away, into nature and being free, having fun and learning about our amazing planet is one of the very few things that takes us away from reality, and right now it is so important. Not only for our mental health but we need to look after our planet, in order for it to look after us. WWF is making a global effort to address the world’s most important environmental challenges: safeguarding the natural world, tackling climate change and enabling people to use only their fair share of natural resources. Together we can build a future where people and nature thrive. By educating our children and future generation as soon as we can is one of the ways we can help. Your support is much appreciated. Find out more by visiting wwf.org.uk

pageSummary: I am going to run 100 miles over January
pageSummaryWhat: I am going to run 100 miles over January
story:
Hi everyone! 

Thanks for taking the time to visit my JustGiving page and for considering donating to this very worthy cause! 

I have decided to run 100 miles over January (I'm definitely not a runner and have been living in a chocolate coma since March!) as I really feel compelled to do something for this amazing charity. 

I hope that I and all of you lovely people can support them to help children around the world who are in desperate need. Your donation could help to give children clean water, food and vaccinations and I would be grateful for any support that you can provide! 

Thank you! 

Caroline xxx

Donating through JustGiving is simple, fast and totally secure. Your details are safe with JustGiving - they'll never sell them on or send unwanted emails. Once you donate, they'll send your money directly to the charity. So it's the most efficient way to donate - saving time and cutting costs for the charity.

charity.name: Unicef UK
story: Throughout the globe Covid-19 has spread rapidly. Although UK and Aus has seen its own share of illness and death we are very lucky enough to have first class healthcare service and government support in this crisis. Unfortunately others around the world are not so lucky. In an attempt to give back to those in need this February I have set myself the challenge to run 100km throughout the month in order to raise money for UNICEF. UNICEF, also known as the united nations children’s fund, is a United Nations agency responsible for providing humanitarian and developmental aid to children worldwide. We extend the invitation to anyone who would like to join us on our ‘Rona Run’ or set your own challenge for the month and help support those in need!
